NWC champion Thor Akerlund.

199
00:08:28,566 --> 00:08:30,626
This film would serve to increase interest

200
00:08:30,666 --> 00:08:32,907
in classic Tetris and our competitive scene going forward.

201
00:08:34,148 --> 00:08:35,969
So, why NES Tetris?

202
00:08:36,889 --> 00:08:37,049
Well,

203
00:08:37,367 --> 00:08:41,029
NES Tetris is considered to be a more basic, difficult, but pure version of Tetris.

204
00:08:41,409 --> 00:08:44,911
Pieces lock down nearly instantly when they land, and you can't slide them around.

205
00:08:45,571 --> 00:08:46,291
It's really strict.

206
00:08:47,052 --> 00:08:48,693
And there's only one piece in the next window.

207
00:08:49,533 --> 00:08:54,815
The basic left and right movement, delayed auto shift behavior, rotation movement rules,

208
00:08:55,636 --> 00:08:57,517
and the like are simple but nuanced.

209
00:08:58,077 --> 00:09:02,059
We call it DAS, where you hold down like a space bar on a keyboard, it'll go once, and

210
00:09:02,099 --> 00:09:04,980
then it'll go a whole bunch of times after that, auto repeating.

211
00:09:05,266 --> 00:09:06,886
That's what we call DAS, and that's something

212
00:09:06,926 --> 00:09:09,187
that you need to know to play NES Tetris effectively.

213
00:09:10,107 --> 00:09:12,227
So it has these mysterious design quirks

214
00:09:12,487 --> 00:09:13,928
that make it compelling and challenging.

215
00:09:14,308 --> 00:09:16,368
But in particular, the scoring displays a maximum

216
00:09:16,388 --> 00:09:20,409
of 999,999 points, with a total score being

217
00:09:20,749 --> 00:09:22,230
just on the brink of possibility.

218
00:09:23,390 --> 00:09:26,210
As such, maxing out Tetris is an effective,

219
00:09:26,570 --> 00:09:29,011
attractive, bucket list gaming achievement,

220
00:09:29,311 --> 00:09:31,692
and a milestone for Tetris eSports hopefuls.

221
00:09:32,289 --> 00:09:37,551
We don't know for sure if this seemingly meticulous balancing was by design or a very happy accident.

222
00:09:38,171 --> 00:09:41,112
But many consider this version of Tetris to be perfect as a result.

223
00:09:41,972 --> 00:09:46,353
So if you are the programmer of this game out there watching, or know who is, please

224
00:09:46,413 --> 00:09:48,894
contact us because we would love to hear from you.

225
00:09:50,634 --> 00:09:56,796
So when a player reaches level 29, NES Tetris pieces fall at a rate of one line per frame,

226
00:09:57,256 --> 00:10:01,537
making horizontal movement nearly impossible, resulting in imminent death.

227
00:10:02,695 --> 00:10:04,615
This effectively acts as a kill screen,

228
00:10:04,875 --> 00:10:06,916
and will instantly end the game for nearly any player.

229
00:10:07,476 --> 00:10:09,236
Only a difficult method of movement,

230
00:10:09,376 --> 00:10:12,057
where a player hits the D-pad faster than 10 times a second

231
00:10:12,357 --> 00:10:14,818
to override the delayed auto-shift called hyper-capping,

232
00:10:15,118 --> 00:10:16,538
can allow for further survival.

233
00:10:18,179 --> 00:10:20,979
The kill screen behavior is unique to NES Tetris,

234
00:10:21,159 --> 00:10:22,620
and it cannot be played forever,

235
00:10:22,960 --> 00:10:24,240
like classic Tetris variants,

236
00:10:24,260 --> 00:10:27,201
such as Game Boy version or Tengen Tetris,

237
00:10:27,781 --> 00:10:29,361
which kind of lets you play forever,

238
00:10:29,381 --> 00:10:30,322
because they're easy like that.

239
00:10:31,562 --> 00:10:35,424
The results of these mechanics create an imminent death situation and round times are around

240
00:10:36,045 --> 00:10:40,528
6 to 9 minutes at most in duration, which are a very good length for an eSports match.

241
00:10:43,110 --> 00:10:47,233
So for a competitive game to be taken seriously as a sport, a standard has to be established

242
00:10:47,293 --> 00:10:48,614
which does not change over time.

243
00:10:49,034 --> 00:10:52,397
With NES Tetris, we have a version of the game that served as the first exposure to

244
00:10:52,417 --> 00:10:57,420
the franchise for many, has a legacy of tournament usage, is well documented, and has stood the

245
00:10:57,440 --> 00:10:58,041
test of time.

246
00:10:58,725 --> 00:11:03,686
As we've seen, players with exceptional skills from the 80s and 90s can still apply their talents even decades later.

247
00:11:04,847 --> 00:11:07,868
Yet the game is still approachable enough for younger or new challengers to succeed.

248
00:11:08,588 --> 00:11:16,390
Our player base doesn't have to worry about new versions, rules, game mechanics, or character nerfs interfering with their mastery of the game.

249
00:11:17,771 --> 00:11:21,352
More recent versions of Tetris have a faster appearance with more hard-drop mechanics.

250
00:11:21,812 --> 00:11:25,133
Things teleport all over the place and they're harder to follow visually.

251
00:11:25,956 --> 00:11:27,317
They allow for more room for error,

252
00:11:27,357 --> 00:11:28,718
like you can keep hitting the rotate button

253
00:11:28,758 --> 00:11:30,159
and the pieces will just bounce around.

254
00:11:30,880 --> 00:11:33,182
But we noticed that the slower visual pace of NES Tetris

255
00:11:33,262 --> 00:11:35,263
actually makes the game easier to learn and comprehend.

256
00:11:35,824 --> 00:11:37,825
Its simplicity ultimately makes it more fun to watch

257
00:11:37,886 --> 00:11:40,307
in an eSports context, with misdrop mistakes

258
00:11:40,568 --> 00:11:42,829
and life or death situations coming across dramatically.

259
00:11:43,890 --> 00:11:45,652
Our tournaments run on original NES hardware

260
00:11:45,672 --> 00:11:47,613
and game cartridges, which are common and inexpensive

261
00:11:47,914 --> 00:11:50,836
to obtain even today, with the game being under five bucks

262
00:11:51,216 --> 00:11:52,918
and old NES system setups well below 50.

263
00:11:54,357 --> 00:11:55,937
Emulation options are also abundant.

264
00:11:56,637 --> 00:11:59,018
A CRT television with no lag is recommended, however.

265
00:11:59,258 --> 00:12:01,599
We run all our events on CRTs, as the precision

266
00:12:01,699 --> 00:12:03,300
of classic Tetris is so demanding,

267
00:12:03,520 --> 00:12:06,401
there are one frame windows of error at high levels of play.

268
00:12:07,101 --> 00:12:09,863
Practice skills are directly applicable to the e-sport.

269
00:12:10,283 --> 00:12:12,343
If someone can consistently score high and max out

270
00:12:12,403 --> 00:12:14,464
on NES Tetris, they have a real shot

271
00:12:14,484 --> 00:12:16,245
at becoming world champion, just by playing

272
00:12:16,265 --> 00:12:17,545
the game within its own rules.

273
00:12:19,426 --> 00:12:20,367
While I won't go into depth.

274
00:12:20,884 --> 00:12:22,565
completely with Tetris play mechanics,

275
00:12:22,866 --> 00:12:24,147
a quick overview should be mentioned

276
00:12:24,187 --> 00:12:26,048
so that the bigger picture of our format will make sense.

277
00:12:26,729 --> 00:12:28,310
In the CTWC, the general strategy

278
00:12:28,330 --> 00:12:29,511
is like most versions of Tetris.

279
00:12:29,931 --> 00:12:31,913
Stack cleanly, leaving a one-block space

280
00:12:31,993 --> 00:12:33,074
on the right edge of the play field,

281
00:12:33,354 --> 00:12:34,775
referred to as a well.

282
00:12:35,496 --> 00:12:38,158
Then use a long bar I tetromino

283
00:12:38,258 --> 00:12:40,020
to score Tetrises as much as possible.

284
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:43,482
For our rule set, Tetrises are critical for scoring.

285
00:12:44,083 --> 00:12:45,384
That's why we go a little overboard

286
00:12:45,444 --> 00:12:46,505
celebrating them sometimes.

287
00:12:46,825 --> 00:12:48,487
They're like a touchdown or a jackpot.

288
00:12:48,900 --> 00:12:50,580
Even if they happen pretty frequently in gameplay,

289
00:12:50,860 --> 00:12:53,041
after a player digs themselves out of a bad situation,

290
00:12:53,101 --> 00:12:54,922
it's really satisfying to see them finally score

291
00:12:54,942 --> 00:12:56,903
that well-deserved Tetris comeback.

292
00:12:57,323 --> 00:12:58,323
Boom, Tetris for you.

293
00:12:59,944 --> 00:13:02,705
The best players will score Tetrises as safely as they can

294
00:13:02,745 --> 00:13:04,085
without wasting scoring potential

295
00:13:04,125 --> 00:13:05,726
by clearing lines that are not Tetrises.

296
00:13:06,166 --> 00:13:08,287
Because of the unique behavior of NES Tetris,

297
00:13:08,527 --> 00:13:09,987
this must be done within the confines

298
00:13:10,007 --> 00:13:13,129
of the 230-line window before the kill screen speed

299
00:13:13,169 --> 00:13:15,970
increase incurs, inevitably ending the game.

300
00:13:17,067 --> 00:13:20,389
As players move in and out of peril as the stacks rise and fall,

301
00:13:20,609 --> 00:13:22,590
the patterns of victory and defeat are illustrated.

302
00:13:22,911 --> 00:13:25,572
The dramatic saves and devastating mistakes are easy to understand,

303
00:13:25,612 --> 00:13:27,833
and with that, the visual satisfaction of a puzzle game,

304
00:13:28,133 --> 00:13:30,535
we feel all those elements are what make this an eSport

305
00:13:30,575 --> 00:13:32,796
that's deceptively compelling and satisfying to watch.

306
00:13:36,358 --> 00:13:38,359
So now I'll mention some of what we learned over the years

307
00:13:38,559 --> 00:13:40,661
and the evolution of our commentary and terminology.

308
00:13:41,241 --> 00:13:43,422
Many common terms exist in Tetris.

309
00:13:43,602 --> 00:13:45,783
For instance, a Tetris well would be one example that...

310
00:13:46,157 --> 00:13:47,417
every version of Tetris would have.

311
00:13:47,717 --> 00:13:49,338
But what's interesting is some unique terms

312
00:13:49,378 --> 00:13:51,319
have come into existence specifically

313
00:13:51,359 --> 00:13:53,980
because of the friction created by the CTWC format

314
00:13:54,300 --> 00:13:55,641
and playing the game competitively

315
00:13:55,941 --> 00:13:57,461
in a way that it was never designed to be.

316
00:13:59,062 --> 00:14:01,563
So pace, some players play at a faster pace than others

317
00:14:01,603 --> 00:14:02,804
by pressing down on the D-pad.

318
00:14:03,084 --> 00:14:05,145
And even though one player may have a higher score currently

319
00:14:05,485 --> 00:14:07,146
if the other player is playing at a slower pace

320
00:14:07,386 --> 00:14:08,686
they may have more lines to work with

321
00:14:08,726 --> 00:14:09,727
to maximize their score.

322
00:14:10,027 --> 00:14:11,988
So that's important in determining potential outcomes

323
00:14:12,048 --> 00:14:13,028
and knowing who's really ahead.

324
00:14:13,368 --> 00:14:15,069
This is something we mention in commentary often.

325
00:14:15,687 --> 00:14:17,888
because it's not really obvious to new viewers.

326
00:14:19,069 --> 00:14:19,449
Droughts.

327
00:14:20,250 --> 00:14:22,732
NES Tetris has harsh, true random pieces

328
00:14:22,772 --> 00:14:25,194
and not a bag randomizer that guarantees piece variety

329
00:14:25,454 --> 00:14:26,735
like modern versions of Tetris.

330
00:14:27,275 --> 00:14:29,417
This results in a potentially long period

331
00:14:29,457 --> 00:14:30,858
without receiving a certain type of piece,

332
00:14:31,138 --> 00:14:33,920
most importantly, that long bar eye tetromino

333
00:14:33,960 --> 00:14:35,841
that's necessary for scoring a Tetris.

334
00:14:36,322 --> 00:14:37,823
So when droughts occur, they can be deadly.

335
00:14:39,124 --> 00:14:39,504
Burn.

336
00:14:40,144 --> 00:14:41,646
Champions must know how to stay alive

337
00:14:41,686 --> 00:14:43,287
and survive these droughts by doing a burn

338
00:14:43,307 --> 00:14:44,668
when necessary to clear lines.

339
00:14:45,061 --> 00:14:46,682
singles or doubles, preferably in a way

340
00:14:46,702 --> 00:14:47,642
that doesn't block the well.

341
00:14:48,543 --> 00:14:50,284
If the Tetris well is blocked badly,

342
00:14:50,384 --> 00:14:51,725
we sometimes call that a dig.

343
00:14:52,405 --> 00:14:54,406
If the dig is successful and the well is open again,

344
00:14:54,426 --> 00:14:56,327
a player is then Tetris ready.

345
00:14:57,948 --> 00:15:00,630
A speed transition is something we highlight in NES Tetris

346
00:15:00,650 --> 00:15:01,890
when a player hits level 19,

347
00:15:02,411 --> 00:15:05,352
since it's an important milestone during CTWC matches,

348
00:15:05,773 --> 00:15:07,193
and you won't see that term used much

349
00:15:07,273 --> 00:15:08,914
outside of this competitive context.

350
00:15:09,755 --> 00:15:11,596
Players need to keep their stack as clean as possible

351
00:15:11,656 --> 00:15:12,717
just before the transition,

352
00:15:13,017 --> 00:15:13,757
and awareness of the

353
00:15:14,325 --> 00:15:16,386
the approach of the transition creates anticipation

354
00:15:16,787 --> 00:15:18,167
as their imminent death awaits.

355
00:15:20,948 --> 00:15:22,329
Conservative and aggressive play.

356
00:15:22,749 --> 00:15:24,390
So one of the most frequent comments we get,

357
00:15:24,410 --> 00:15:25,631
especially with our commentary,

358
00:15:25,671 --> 00:15:27,772
is how we mention aggressive or conservative play.

359
00:15:28,512 --> 00:15:29,773
How do you play Tetris aggressively?

360
00:15:30,013 --> 00:15:32,894
You punch your opponent that's sitting next to you?

361
00:15:33,574 --> 00:15:36,176
No, no, what we mean by that is by playing aggressively,

362
00:15:36,496 --> 00:15:39,377
more risks are taken to absolutely maximize the score

363
00:15:39,417 --> 00:15:40,878
by not burning off any unnecessary

364
00:15:40,918 --> 00:15:41,978
singles, doubles, or triples.

365
00:15:42,385 --> 00:15:44,246
Conversely, playing more safely and burning more lines

366
00:15:44,266 --> 00:15:46,387
will keep you out of trouble, but it won't score as much.

367
00:15:46,907 --> 00:15:48,288
Play too aggressively and you could end up

368
00:15:48,328 --> 00:15:50,789
topping out and gaming over, but play too conservatively

369
00:15:51,069 --> 00:15:52,770
and your opponent will kick your ass with score.

370
00:15:54,250 --> 00:15:56,531
So terminology helps us be aware of all these factors

371
00:15:56,571 --> 00:15:57,832
that determine the outcome of a match.

372
00:15:58,212 --> 00:16:00,293
We can then commentate on them and step with the players

373
00:16:00,613 --> 00:16:03,114
as their play styles and personalities become a factor

374
00:16:03,134 --> 00:16:04,895
in telling the story that's unfolding

375
00:16:05,215 --> 00:16:07,076
while providing a better understanding of the game.

376
00:16:07,836 --> 00:16:10,097
Playful and relatable metaphors like digging

377
00:16:10,857 --> 00:16:11,898
add fun to the commentary.

378
00:16:12,437 --> 00:16:14,658
So there's more to it than just saying, boom, Tetris a lot,

379
00:16:14,818 --> 00:16:16,740
even though I think that helps excite people too.

380
00:16:18,641 --> 00:16:19,541
So check out this screen.

381
00:16:20,262 --> 00:16:22,203
Do you notice anything interesting about this situation,

382
00:16:22,263 --> 00:16:23,804
keeping in mind that these players are playing

383
00:16:23,844 --> 00:16:25,686
on two separate NES systems and TVs?

384
00:16:27,847 --> 00:16:28,348
Exactly.

385
00:16:29,308 --> 00:16:31,049
Both players get the same pieces.

386
00:16:32,130 --> 00:16:34,212
So, a special cartridge pass-through device,

387
00:16:34,412 --> 00:16:35,552
sort of like a Game Genie,

388
00:16:36,113 --> 00:16:37,294
you guys know what a Game Genie is?

389
00:16:38,254 --> 00:16:38,534
All right.

390
00:16:39,295 --> 00:16:41,517
Works with the original NES Tetris cartridge attached.

391
00:16:42,063 --> 00:16:44,624
and provides the same random pea seed for both players

392
00:16:44,664 --> 00:16:45,584
in a one-on-one match.

393
00:16:46,204 --> 00:16:48,465
Although we found that top-level players could be very

394
00:16:48,505 --> 00:16:50,145
consistent no matter what the pea set was,

395
00:16:50,385 --> 00:16:52,166
there was always a question of whether or not

396
00:16:52,286 --> 00:16:53,846
one player had an advantage over the other

397
00:16:53,886 --> 00:16:55,306
if they had different pieces in the match.

398
00:16:55,846 --> 00:16:58,267
With the same pieces for both players now in the same round,

399
00:16:58,547 --> 00:17:00,968
there would never be any doubt of that again,

400
00:17:01,688 --> 00:17:03,608
and that the outcome would be based on skill alone.

401
00:17:04,168 --> 00:17:06,469
So a referee rolls the dice prior to the round starting,

402
00:17:06,909 --> 00:17:08,029
and players will enter the number

403
00:17:08,089 --> 00:17:09,189
rolled, which will generate one of 1,000

404
00:17:09,689 --> 00:17:10,870
possible random pea seeds.

405
00:17:12,630 --> 00:17:13,830
The players don't see the same thing

406
00:17:13,850 --> 00:17:15,071
that the broadcast viewers do.

407
00:17:16,231 --> 00:17:19,433
So we have this overlay that's designed by Trey Harrison.

408
00:17:19,913 --> 00:17:22,534
And that's what facilitates not only the gameplay screens

409
00:17:22,814 --> 00:17:24,095
and the competitor face cams,

410
00:17:24,355 --> 00:17:26,516
but it processes and reinterprets game information

411
00:17:26,556 --> 00:17:28,736
in real time, assisting us show runners

412
00:17:28,917 --> 00:17:30,397
and increasing excitement for viewers.

413
00:17:30,997 --> 00:17:33,298
I'll go into a bit of detail on that now.

414
00:17:35,079 --> 00:17:38,581
So Score Readout provides automated math

415
00:17:38,741 --> 00:17:40,622
with optical character recognition,

416
00:17:40,902 --> 00:17:42,122
highlighting the score differential.

417
00:17:42,609 --> 00:17:44,670
Players who are behind will have their difference highlighted

418
00:17:44,731 --> 00:17:46,312
in red, while players who are ahead

419
00:17:46,352 --> 00:17:47,953
will have the difference highlighted in green.

420
00:17:49,534 --> 00:17:51,535
This area that you see at the bottom of the screen

421
00:17:51,555 --> 00:17:52,636
has a bunch of different stats.

422
00:17:53,216 --> 00:17:55,638
And those stats are not usually available in the game.

423
00:17:55,678 --> 00:17:57,879
So what the game is actually, or what our overlay is doing,

424
00:17:57,959 --> 00:17:59,420
is it's looking at the game.

425
00:17:59,440 --> 00:18:00,421
And every time it sees something,

426
00:18:00,461 --> 00:18:02,822
it's actually keeping that data and processing it,

427
00:18:03,223 --> 00:18:05,764
and then reinterpreting that data for viewers.

428
00:18:06,805 --> 00:18:09,727
So TRT stands for Tetris Percentage Rate,

429
00:18:09,867 --> 00:18:10,928
or the percentage of lines.

430
00:18:11,694 --> 00:18:12,975
are that have come from Tetrises.

431
00:18:13,355 --> 00:18:15,516
This is a good measure for how well a player is scoring.

432
00:18:15,916 --> 00:18:18,937
To max out the score, a player needs about 60% or higher

433
00:18:19,317 --> 00:18:20,418
percentage of Tetris lines.

434
00:18:21,618 --> 00:18:24,320
BRN stands for burn lines, or how many lines

435
00:18:24,340 --> 00:18:25,660
have been burned between Tetrises.

436
00:18:27,101 --> 00:18:29,222
Then, of course, a glowing long red bar,

437
00:18:30,482 --> 00:18:32,383
if that shows up in our overlay, that

438
00:18:32,403 --> 00:18:33,704
means a drought is taking place.

439
00:18:34,044 --> 00:18:36,145
The number of pieces spawned since the last long bar

440
00:18:36,185 --> 00:18:38,586
or eyepiece appeared is displayed below the icon.

441
00:18:40,291 --> 00:18:42,572
And there's a player name and match wins indicator.

442
00:18:42,933 --> 00:18:45,194
The red hearts indicate the number of matches won

443
00:18:45,214 --> 00:18:45,634
in the set.

444
00:18:47,235 --> 00:18:50,877
And this main gameplay area has a context-sensitive overlay

445
00:18:50,898 --> 00:18:54,180
that replaces dead screens and menus with logos and stats

446
00:18:54,220 --> 00:18:55,600
which improve viewer comprehension.

447
00:18:57,321 --> 00:18:59,343
Even more useful data and stats will be displayed here

448
00:18:59,423 --> 00:19:00,443
after a player tops out.

449
00:19:01,564 --> 00:19:03,105
And of course, the faces of the competitors

450
00:19:03,145 --> 00:19:05,466
are displayed nice and large, bringing the human element

451
00:19:05,907 --> 00:19:07,688
front and center, and they're always visible.

452
00:19:10,991 --> 00:19:13,832
So now to talk a little bit about the path to the championship for a player.

453
00:19:14,512 --> 00:19:17,874
We started this just as a yearly event, but now we hold regionals at satellite events

454
00:19:17,914 --> 00:19:18,614
all around the world.

455
00:19:19,175 --> 00:19:23,216
Following Portland Retro Gaming Expo's success came other gaming events growing in their

456
00:19:23,236 --> 00:19:28,339
own markets, such as Game On Expo in Phoenix, Arizona, and Retro City Fest in Southern California.

457
00:19:28,979 --> 00:19:33,501
As this network of local convention communities began to form, these up-and-coming shows became

458
00:19:33,561 --> 00:19:35,162
perfect sites for our regional events.

459
00:19:35,935 --> 00:19:38,397
Last year, we had five regional qualifier events in the US

460
00:19:38,457 --> 00:19:40,718
and partnered with RetroHK Gaming Expo

461
00:19:40,958 --> 00:19:43,860
for our events in Europe, Asia, and regionals

462
00:19:43,900 --> 00:19:46,182
in Hong Kong, Singapore, and Gamescom in Germany.

463
00:19:46,962 --> 00:19:49,664
While we continued the Classic Tetris European Championship,

464
00:19:50,084 --> 00:19:52,005
our first event partner, and that one's

465
00:19:52,025 --> 00:19:53,106
been going for a few years now.

466
00:19:54,547 --> 00:19:55,847
While participating in these regionals

467
00:19:55,907 --> 00:19:57,749
is not required to enter the world championships,

468
00:19:58,049 --> 00:19:59,290
it's a nice throwback to the days

469
00:19:59,330 --> 00:20:01,711
when console companies would hold tours where anyone

470
00:20:01,751 --> 00:20:03,372
of any age could come and enter in their region

471
00:20:03,672 --> 00:20:05,633
and win a trip for their shot at the world title.

472
00:20:06,209 --> 00:20:08,071
And it's great to be able to give those kinds of opportunities

473
00:20:08,111 --> 00:20:08,911
to players once again.

474
00:20:09,572 --> 00:20:11,934
Growing our format while making the tournament more accessible

475
00:20:12,274 --> 00:20:14,996
and adding incentives for the players is a win for everyone involved.

476
00:20:15,256 --> 00:20:17,538
And these growing events, it's nice to have something

477
00:20:17,558 --> 00:20:19,540
that's kind of established at their show,

478
00:20:19,640 --> 00:20:20,901
so people will want to come out to it.

479
00:20:23,062 --> 00:20:26,085
So for our rules and format, qualifying is really simple.

480
00:20:26,545 --> 00:20:28,707
In the qualifying stage, players just play NES Tetris

481
00:20:28,727 --> 00:20:30,989
throughout the day and try to get the highest score that they can.

482
00:20:31,469 --> 00:20:33,811
They can either line up and make repeated attempts

483
00:20:33,851 --> 00:20:35,212
getting in line again after they lose,

484
00:20:35,784 --> 00:20:37,065
or rent a station for a fee.

485
00:20:37,946 --> 00:20:41,089
These qualifying runs are literally just playing the stock game by themselves and trying for

486
00:20:41,109 --> 00:20:41,489
a score.

487
00:20:41,989 --> 00:20:46,634
And this one-to-one performance parity between practicing at home and qualifying makes it

488
00:20:46,694 --> 00:20:53,861
understandable and approachable for hopeful Tetris contenders, and is similar to the player

489
00:20:53,921 --> 00:20:56,003
versus player mechanics that are going to follow that.

490
00:20:57,364 --> 00:21:00,747
At the end of the qualifying period, the top scores, eight for a regional

491
00:21:01,083 --> 00:21:03,184
where 32 for the World Championships are rounded up

492
00:21:03,224 --> 00:21:04,484
and entered into a seeded bracket

493
00:21:04,504 --> 00:21:05,605
for the one-on-one matchups.

494
00:21:07,185 --> 00:21:09,385
The bracketed matches are a one-on-one score contest.

495
00:21:09,746 --> 00:21:11,566
Each player plays on a separate NES station.

496
00:21:12,106 --> 00:21:13,506
Games are started simultaneously,

497
00:21:14,647 --> 00:21:17,227
and they go for a score that can beat their opponents.

498
00:21:18,248 --> 00:21:20,968
There's no direct interaction between the play fields.

499
00:21:21,928 --> 00:21:23,849
But if you notice what's going on in that GIF,

500
00:21:24,469 --> 00:21:26,630
there's no garbage sending lines unlike some versions

501
00:21:26,670 --> 00:21:27,170
of Tetris.

502
00:21:27,630 --> 00:21:29,830
However, players can keep an eye.

503
00:21:30,283 --> 00:21:33,005
on their opponent's screen as a strategy, if they so choose

504
00:21:33,045 --> 00:21:35,847
to do so, and can vary their aggression accordingly.

505
00:21:36,628 --> 00:21:39,329
Interestingly, I noticed that younger players do this far more

506
00:21:39,369 --> 00:21:40,450
frequently than the veterans.

507
00:21:42,912 --> 00:21:43,672
Games start at level 18

508
00:21:44,092 --> 00:21:46,034
as it facilitates the highest scoring potential.

