00:43:50,006 --> 00:43:50,747
licensee at the time.

999
00:43:50,807 --> 00:43:52,528
But it was just insurmountable.

1000
00:43:52,568 --> 00:43:54,750
We didn't think that we'd be able to do one in 2012.

1001
00:43:55,371 --> 00:43:56,352
Things looked grim, and it looked

1002
00:43:56,392 --> 00:43:58,213
like we were going to top out and game over.

1003
00:43:59,822 --> 00:44:00,902
But we were saved by a miracle.

1004
00:44:01,223 --> 00:44:03,704
For our third year, we were encouraged by Chuck Van Pelt,

1005
00:44:03,724 --> 00:44:05,125
who runs the Portland Retro Gaming Expo,

1006
00:44:05,145 --> 00:44:06,446
to have the event at his show,

1007
00:44:06,786 --> 00:44:08,928
since some of our founders, like Adam and Robin, were local.

1008
00:44:09,508 --> 00:44:10,309
So we gave it a shot.

1009
00:44:10,969 --> 00:44:12,330
And I didn't want to go there,

1010
00:44:12,390 --> 00:44:13,291
because I was just like, man,

1011
00:44:13,311 --> 00:44:14,952
I'm going to all these anime cons

1012
00:44:14,972 --> 00:44:16,673
and all these video game events.

1013
00:44:16,733 --> 00:44:18,474
And I didn't want to have to go to another state

1014
00:44:18,895 --> 00:44:21,416
to do this thing, but I was like, you know what?

1015
00:44:22,037 --> 00:44:23,158
I like what you guys are doing,

1016
00:44:23,418 --> 00:44:24,559
and I felt a connection to it.

1017
00:44:24,619 --> 00:44:26,860
So I went up there, and I slept on Adam's floor,

1018
00:44:26,880 --> 00:44:28,841
and I'm like, all right, I'll go and commentate your thing.

1019
00:44:29,531 --> 00:44:32,252
So I went there and I went to the Portland Retro Gaming Expo

1020
00:44:32,553 --> 00:44:33,473
and I freaking loved it.

1021
00:44:33,673 --> 00:44:35,794
Like all these retro games, I just like, you know,

1022
00:44:36,074 --> 00:44:37,875
bought all this stuff that I couldn't get anywhere else

1023
00:44:37,915 --> 00:44:40,056
and I liked the culture and what they did

1024
00:44:40,076 --> 00:44:40,937
for retro gaming there.

1025
00:44:41,017 --> 00:44:43,358
So even if I didn't have this gig,

1026
00:44:43,478 --> 00:44:46,320
I would just go there just to go and have fun at the expo

1027
00:44:46,380 --> 00:44:47,560
and hang out with my friends and stuff.

1028
00:44:47,600 --> 00:44:48,701
So great show.

1029
00:44:50,402 --> 00:44:52,523
So having the tournament at the Retro Gaming Expo

1030
00:44:52,543 --> 00:44:54,584
gave us an excited built-in audience for free.

1031
00:44:54,904 --> 00:44:56,325
And this was a huge turning point for us.

1032
00:44:57,146 --> 00:44:59,487
Because with the CTWC now having a permanent home,

1033
00:44:59,727 --> 00:45:00,888
we didn't have to worry about the venue

1034
00:45:00,928 --> 00:45:01,829
and the other logistics,

1035
00:45:01,869 --> 00:45:03,570
and it freed up our time and resources

1036
00:45:03,590 --> 00:45:04,770
to focus on what mattered most,

1037
00:45:05,311 --> 00:45:06,792
and expand and improve the tournament.

1038
00:45:07,952 --> 00:45:10,674
So they experienced, the Portland Retro Gaming Expo

1039
00:45:10,714 --> 00:45:13,155
experienced a huge surge in growth around that time,

1040
00:45:13,215 --> 00:45:14,316
and we were able to grow with it.

1041
00:45:14,856 --> 00:45:17,078
As interest in the CTWC increased in recent years,

1042
00:45:17,358 --> 00:45:18,899
more people are now traveling Portland

1043
00:45:18,959 --> 00:45:21,380
specifically to compete in and spectate the CTWC.

1044
00:45:21,901 --> 00:45:23,462
Symbiotic relationships can be pretty awesome.

1045
00:45:24,912 --> 00:45:28,693
So when we first started this, we didn't know whether we'd be able to get official backing

1046
00:45:28,733 --> 00:45:31,615
and approval from the IP holders of Tetris, even though I used to work for them.

1047
00:45:32,115 --> 00:45:33,415
The Tetris company are BPS.

1048
00:45:33,836 --> 00:45:38,978
So we did contact them, and Hank showed up at our first tournament, and Alexei even sent

1049
00:45:39,018 --> 00:45:39,398
a video.

1050
00:45:39,418 --> 00:45:39,998
It was pretty cool.

1051
00:45:40,879 --> 00:45:44,100
We put the honest work and effort into it, and I think that's why we were able to get

1052
00:45:44,140 --> 00:45:45,441
them to do that for our first event.

1053
00:45:46,001 --> 00:45:50,083
We would later see involvement from companies like EA, Ubisoft, Sega, and most recently

1054
00:45:50,123 --> 00:45:51,463
Enhance, with Tetris Effect.

1055
00:45:52,084 --> 00:45:54,165
Our community and professionalism was a key part of that.

1056
00:45:54,763 --> 00:45:56,604
members of our staff and founders having backgrounds

1057
00:45:56,644 --> 00:45:58,744
in production, events, competitive gaming,

1058
00:45:58,784 --> 00:46:00,145
and eSports played a huge factor.

1059
00:46:01,025 --> 00:46:04,886
So this grassroots yet official eSports event dream,

1060
00:46:05,366 --> 00:46:05,986
it can be done.

1061
00:46:06,666 --> 00:46:09,547
And with a brand as iconic and important as Tetris,

1062
00:46:10,127 --> 00:46:13,908
we're very happy that it's not only growing new competitors

1063
00:46:13,968 --> 00:46:16,188
and champions, but what we do reflects back positively

1064
00:46:16,568 --> 00:46:18,048
back on the Tetris brand and the games

1065
00:46:18,068 --> 00:46:19,129
that we all love and cherish.

1066
00:46:20,689 --> 00:46:22,409
So while the focus of our tournament activities

1067
00:46:22,469 --> 00:46:23,750
is the classic NES Tetris,

1068
00:46:24,035 --> 00:46:26,477
We also help promote the current or newest versions of it.

1069
00:46:27,058 --> 00:46:29,239
Most recently, we partnered with Enhanced Games

1070
00:46:29,259 --> 00:46:30,981
for Tetris Effect on PlayStation VR,

1071
00:46:31,221 --> 00:46:34,203
with special demos at the CTWC,

1072
00:46:34,524 --> 00:46:37,046
and legendary game designer Tetsuya Mizuguchi present.

1073
00:46:37,266 --> 00:46:38,226
I didn't even know he was coming,

1074
00:46:38,246 --> 00:46:39,968
and when he showed up, I almost had a heart attack.

1075
00:46:41,349 --> 00:46:43,350
He's actually here this year too at GDC,

1076
00:46:43,390 --> 00:46:46,753
so hopefully some of you have seen his session as well.

1077
00:46:47,694 --> 00:46:50,376
Top players in our Tetris community

1078
00:46:50,496 --> 00:46:52,738
were also on hand to provide developer feedback for them.

1079
00:46:53,182 --> 00:46:54,902
and to show off their moves in a special tournament.

1080
00:46:56,043 --> 00:46:57,523
We also have side tournaments on popular,

1081
00:46:57,563 --> 00:46:59,924
newer Tetris variants such as Tetris the Grandmaster,

1082
00:47:00,484 --> 00:47:01,485
those are some arcade games.

1083
00:47:02,285 --> 00:47:05,446
And the CTWC has then become a celebration

1084
00:47:05,466 --> 00:47:08,027
of all things Tetris, and licensee partners

1085
00:47:08,047 --> 00:47:10,268
and IP holders all look forward to every year

1086
00:47:10,328 --> 00:47:11,609
bringing the old and new together.

1087
00:47:13,849 --> 00:47:15,290
So even prior to our last tournament,

1088
00:47:15,410 --> 00:47:17,951
one of our CTWC stars and organizers, Trey Harrison,

1089
00:47:18,271 --> 00:47:19,331
was featured in a pre-released

1090
00:47:19,351 --> 00:47:21,232
Tetris Effect VR demo video on YouTube.

1091
00:47:21,825 --> 00:47:23,765
And it quickly gained 8 million plus views,

1092
00:47:23,785 --> 00:47:25,105
helping to promote the upcoming title.

1093
00:47:26,166 --> 00:47:28,526
We look forward to helping strengthen the Tetris brand

1094
00:47:28,546 --> 00:47:30,466
in ways like this going on into the future.

1095
00:47:31,947 --> 00:47:32,927
So here's some takeaways.

1096
00:47:33,667 --> 00:47:35,247
Know your game well, inside and out,

1097
00:47:35,687 --> 00:47:38,008
if you want to have an e-sport kind of like happen for it.

1098
00:47:38,248 --> 00:47:40,028
But be sure to reach out and enlist experts

1099
00:47:40,068 --> 00:47:41,888
on the game who know its rules, mechanics.

1100
00:47:44,389 --> 00:47:45,869
Oh, making sure your video signal's OK.

1101
00:47:46,029 --> 00:47:46,229
OK.

1102
00:47:48,090 --> 00:47:50,130
Make sure that you enlist experts on the game who

1103
00:47:51,980 --> 00:47:54,763
rules, mechanics, and nuances, because they might also

1104
00:47:54,803 --> 00:47:55,984
become your potential competitors

1105
00:47:56,244 --> 00:47:57,485
and the heroes of your e-sport.

1106
00:47:58,186 --> 00:48:00,688
The CTWC wouldn't have started had this step not

1107
00:48:00,708 --> 00:48:01,709
been taken a decade ago.

1108
00:48:03,210 --> 00:48:05,812
A great rule set can make almost any game fun for competition.

1109
00:48:06,193 --> 00:48:07,634
So find what's most fun about your game

1110
00:48:07,654 --> 00:48:09,175
and bring out the competitive aspect of it.

1111
00:48:09,596 --> 00:48:11,237
For example, the best excitement in Tetris

1112
00:48:11,277 --> 00:48:13,679
is about building and scoring Tetrises,

1113
00:48:13,739 --> 00:48:17,663
pushing the limits of survival, not just playing fast or playing

1114
00:48:17,683 --> 00:48:17,963
forever.

1115
00:48:19,365 --> 00:48:21,526
Stats and metrics that encourage analysis and discussion

1116
00:48:21,567 --> 00:48:23,548
and adding elements that make it easier for audiences

1117
00:48:23,588 --> 00:48:24,748
to understand what's going on,

1118
00:48:25,088 --> 00:48:26,749
help make it more fun to watch,

1119
00:48:27,109 --> 00:48:28,330
leading to audience expansion.

1120
00:48:29,110 --> 00:48:30,651
And if a high-tech method of conveying it

1121
00:48:30,931 --> 00:48:32,212
isn't possible like what we're doing,

1122
00:48:32,452 --> 00:48:33,613
you can just do it through commentary.

1123
00:48:35,054 --> 00:48:37,235
So we're nerdy, we're quirky, and we're super welcoming

1124
00:48:37,735 --> 00:48:39,096
with strong sportsmanship,

1125
00:48:39,316 --> 00:48:41,077
and we all love seeing each other succeed.

1126
00:48:41,677 --> 00:48:43,198
And one awesome thing that our social media

1127
00:48:43,218 --> 00:48:45,299
has been doing lately is posting and retweeting

1128
00:48:45,339 --> 00:48:47,480
the accomplishments of all walks of players

1129
00:48:47,520 --> 00:48:48,861
on their journey through Tetris mastery.

1130
00:48:49,177 --> 00:48:50,498
whether it be a new personal best

1131
00:48:50,938 --> 00:48:52,539
in an attempt to max out NES Tetris,

1132
00:48:52,800 --> 00:48:55,541
or finally winning that first Victory Royale on Tetris 99.

1133
00:48:56,522 --> 00:48:57,863
Celebrating each other's successes

1134
00:48:58,023 --> 00:48:59,504
in the nature of what we do.

1135
00:49:01,605 --> 00:49:03,827
And we're very proud that we love being an example

1136
00:49:03,847 --> 00:49:06,588
of the very best of what video games can represent.

1137
00:49:07,469 --> 00:49:09,310
When you have a story in which a 16-year-old kid

1138
00:49:09,590 --> 00:49:12,032
watched our championships, got into it because of the memes,

1139
00:49:12,352 --> 00:49:13,813
learned from the world champion on Twitch,

1140
00:49:14,233 --> 00:49:16,335
then became champion himself in just a year.

1141
00:49:16,973 --> 00:49:20,394
the dream of eSports suddenly becomes within reach for everyone.

1142
00:49:22,235 --> 00:49:24,615
So, find partners with common goals and audiences.

1143
00:49:25,795 --> 00:49:28,856
Retro gaming events made a lot of sense for us

1144
00:49:28,936 --> 00:49:33,337
because having a common audience, you know, it brought

1145
00:49:33,437 --> 00:49:36,318
our players to their event and it gave us an audience.

1146
00:49:36,678 --> 00:49:39,358
Like, that just watched our stuff because it was going on in the background.

1147
00:49:40,438 --> 00:49:44,939
I'm still shocked that people are okay with missing out on all those great deals of retro games that happen when the show is closing,

1148
00:49:44,999 --> 00:49:45,940
but, you know, that's just me.

1149
00:49:47,447 --> 00:49:50,688
For those communities seeking sponsorship or endorsements

1150
00:49:50,908 --> 00:49:53,629
from events and IP holders, showing a strength of community

1151
00:49:53,669 --> 00:49:55,190
and running events professionally, even

1152
00:49:55,250 --> 00:49:58,051
without their official blessing, can potentially earn it.

1153
00:49:58,592 --> 00:50:00,212
We're fortunate things happen the way they did,

1154
00:50:00,513 --> 00:50:01,993
but there are other examples of this happening,

1155
00:50:02,053 --> 00:50:04,374
such as in the fighting game scene or another NES

1156
00:50:04,834 --> 00:50:07,356
favorite, Tecmo Bowl, with the Tecmo Madison tournaments.

1157
00:50:08,096 --> 00:50:10,257
The prospect of growing a strong e-sports presence

1158
00:50:10,317 --> 00:50:11,718
is attractive to many IP holders.

1159
00:50:11,998 --> 00:50:14,039
So if you're a fan with a plan and a good community,

1160
00:50:14,179 --> 00:50:14,819
it may be possible.

1161
00:50:16,272 --> 00:50:18,294
Our internet presence started off small and humble,

1162
00:50:18,634 --> 00:50:19,815
but we didn't let that deter us

1163
00:50:19,835 --> 00:50:20,855
from getting our stuff out there.

1164
00:50:21,476 --> 00:50:24,458
My gut reaction to seeing my own repetitive commentary,

1165
00:50:25,218 --> 00:50:26,079
I would have been embarrassed

1166
00:50:26,159 --> 00:50:27,200
and I would have wanted to hide it.

1167
00:50:27,760 --> 00:50:28,821
But that would have been a mistake

1168
00:50:28,901 --> 00:50:30,742
because it turned into this positive meme

1169
00:50:30,762 --> 00:50:31,783
that a lot of people love.

1170
00:50:32,583 --> 00:50:34,485
So don't be too embarrassed about your stuff

1171
00:50:34,585 --> 00:50:36,006
because you never know what would happen.

1172
00:50:37,567 --> 00:50:39,568
And now we're gonna get into a bonus takeaway,

1173
00:50:39,608 --> 00:50:40,629
which is as a game designer,

1174
00:50:40,649 --> 00:50:42,250
I feel compelled to take what I've observed

1175
00:50:42,670 --> 00:50:44,411
and see if it could be applied to games and development.

1176
00:50:45,371 --> 00:50:46,172
So I thought I'd touch on it.

1177
00:50:47,412 --> 00:50:50,534
So while NES Tetris has a max-out as a built-in life goal,

1178
00:50:51,155 --> 00:50:53,056
like a bucket list thing, that's not

1179
00:50:53,076 --> 00:50:55,077
to say that such goals or mechanics can't be devised

1180
00:50:55,177 --> 00:50:56,578
by design for games and development.

1181
00:50:57,058 --> 00:50:57,739
It doesn't have to be score.

1182
00:50:57,759 --> 00:50:59,080
It could be something like a perfect run

1183
00:50:59,120 --> 00:51:01,641
or performing a time-based challenge or something like that.

1184
00:51:02,642 --> 00:51:05,504
Achieving grandmaster status in the Tetris Grandmaster games,

1185
00:51:06,124 --> 00:51:07,685
which are the arcade ones by Eureka,

1186
00:51:08,362 --> 00:51:10,644
You have to survive invisible Tetris in the endgame credits,

1187
00:51:10,664 --> 00:51:12,625
and that's an example of an intentionally designed goal

1188
00:51:12,665 --> 00:51:14,566
for players to chase to prove their skill

1189
00:51:14,606 --> 00:51:15,947
in a totally different Tetris game.

1190
00:51:16,588 --> 00:51:19,129
What your game can offer to facilitate the proof of skill

1191
00:51:19,169 --> 00:51:21,591
over time and true mastery is something to think about.

1192
00:51:22,211 --> 00:51:23,572
If you implement skill-based goals,

1193
00:51:23,612 --> 00:51:25,493
it can drive the competitive instinct and discussion,

1194
00:51:25,813 --> 00:51:27,254
which can start a competitive community.

1195
00:51:28,555 --> 00:51:30,196
If your game has mechanics that are unique to it,

1196
00:51:30,416 --> 00:51:31,797
does it have easy-to-understand,

1197
00:51:32,098 --> 00:51:33,518
interesting terminology to back it up?

1198
00:51:34,099 --> 00:51:35,800
How about fun metaphors that work for it?

1199
00:51:36,460 --> 00:51:37,261
Words like Tetris.

1200
00:51:37,795 --> 00:51:40,057
Burns, well, drought, and dig,

1201
00:51:40,897 --> 00:51:43,459
help define our gameplay identity and encourage commentary.

1202
00:51:44,540 --> 00:51:47,341
And sports celebratory verb terms like touchdown,

1203
00:51:47,681 --> 00:51:53,545
slam dunk, and goal from soccer are all iconic.

1204
00:51:54,206 --> 00:51:55,706
We've got, boom, Tetris for Jeff,

1205
00:51:56,327 --> 00:51:58,208
which is great because it can be an encouragement,

1206
00:51:58,928 --> 00:52:01,950
exclamation, or just a celebration.

1207
00:52:03,171 --> 00:52:05,092
So what terms and languages does your game have

1208
00:52:05,152 --> 00:52:06,973
and can it be improved for esports viability?

1209
00:52:09,146 --> 00:52:12,268
Focus on the mechanic of the game that is most fun or unique, and expand on that to

1210
00:52:12,308 --> 00:52:16,130
find what the best eSport context or competitive heart of your game are.

1211
00:52:16,710 --> 00:52:21,153
Think of your game as a tool for facilitating competition, even if it might not be designed

1212
00:52:21,193 --> 00:52:22,114
to do that at first.

1213
00:52:22,774 --> 00:52:27,697
Experiment and add things like scores, timers, extra modes, handicaps or new metrics, and

1214
00:52:27,737 --> 00:52:28,938
something competitive may be born.

1215
00:52:29,518 --> 00:52:32,940
If you have no two-player or versus mode, well, what if you put two setups side by side?

1216
00:52:33,600 --> 00:52:34,501
Having a score time

1217
00:52:35,355 --> 00:52:37,756
or time race usually works even in the worst case scenario

1218
00:52:37,796 --> 00:52:39,056
and that's what we did in the 90s

1219
00:52:39,116 --> 00:52:41,758
when we had these big massive console gaming competitions.

1220
00:52:43,458 --> 00:52:45,359
So does your game have a finishing moment,

1221
00:52:45,779 --> 00:52:47,040
like a game over or a death?

1222
00:52:47,380 --> 00:52:48,861
In the best sporting events and competitions,

1223
00:52:48,881 --> 00:52:50,581
there's huge and impactful moments,

1224
00:52:50,962 --> 00:52:52,342
like a knockout punch for boxing

1225
00:52:52,382 --> 00:52:54,443
is a good relatable analogy for a fighting game.

1226
00:52:55,023 --> 00:52:57,484
In Tetris, for us, it's topping out as our death mechanism.

1227
00:52:58,185 --> 00:53:01,046
So while we could've gone for something

1228
00:53:01,066 --> 00:53:03,087
like a three minute score attack or a first to 25 lines race.

1229
00:53:04,131 --> 00:53:06,692
that wouldn't have the impact of impending doom

1230
00:53:06,712 --> 00:53:08,072
that we have in NES Tetris.

1231
00:53:08,573 --> 00:53:10,193
So forcing people to play to the kill screen

1232
00:53:10,213 --> 00:53:12,534
is actually kind of an addicting part of what we do.

1233
00:53:13,074 --> 00:53:15,435
Take advantage of the drama of a finish with commentary

1234
00:53:15,695 --> 00:53:16,995
and build it up however you can.

1235
00:53:18,516 --> 00:53:19,896
Now for any competitive context,

1236
00:53:20,137 --> 00:53:22,157
the game and competition has to facilitate fairness.

1237
00:53:22,717 --> 00:53:25,058
Even for Tetris, having the RNG of the piece

1238
00:53:25,098 --> 00:53:26,199
being the same between players

1239
00:53:26,259 --> 00:53:28,139
is one of the things that made a big difference

1240
00:53:28,179 --> 00:53:30,200
in making the game feel legitimate and competitive.

1241
00:53:30,900 --> 00:53:32,881
Some games implement things like rubber banding.

1242
00:53:33,271 --> 00:53:34,832
Like in a racing game, they artificially cheat

1243
00:53:34,852 --> 00:53:37,192
for the player that's behind to make them catch up,

1244
00:53:37,232 --> 00:53:38,713
to make the games more fun for noobs.

1245
00:53:39,393 --> 00:53:42,374
Mario Party and Mario Kart are some pretty bad offenders.

1246
00:53:43,555 --> 00:53:46,196
But unfairness like that can outright prevent a game

1247
00:53:46,216 --> 00:53:48,157
from being considered viable for eSports.

1248
00:53:49,037 --> 00:53:51,218
So I suggest restricting those elements to beginner modes,

1249
00:53:51,598 --> 00:53:54,459
kids modes, or allow options to control or disable them,

1250
00:53:54,839 --> 00:53:56,140
and be transparent with your players.

1251
00:53:58,180 --> 00:54:01,842
So this past year, we've gained an unprecedented amount

1252
00:54:01,862 --> 00:54:02,682
of mainstream coverage.

1253
00:54:03,025 --> 00:54:06,227
on everything from Fox News, CTV Canada, to the BBC.

1254
00:54:06,888 --> 00:54:08,869
I think it's the inviting competitive atmosphere

1255
00:54:08,889 --> 00:54:10,790
is what gave us stories like Joseph Saley's.

1256
00:54:11,971 --> 00:54:14,513
As a video game champion myself, starting out as a kid,

1257
00:54:14,913 --> 00:54:16,995
being inspired by TV shows like Starcade

1258
00:54:17,275 --> 00:54:18,696
and other classic gaming competitions,

1259
00:54:19,136 --> 00:54:21,638
that's what allowed me to find my path to success in life.

1260
00:54:22,039 --> 00:54:23,900
And now to be involved in the CTWC

1261
00:54:23,960 --> 00:54:26,602
and seeing it inspire a new generation of champions,

1262
00:54:27,282 --> 00:54:28,743
it's really like a dream come true.

1263
00:54:29,244 --> 00:54:30,445
I feel like I've come full circle.

1264
00:54:31,523 --> 00:54:33,304
So if you have a game franchise or IP,

1265
00:54:33,684 --> 00:54:35,585
or are involved in a games community

1266
00:54:35,665 --> 00:54:37,086
and want to grow an eSports presence,

1267
00:54:37,366 --> 00:54:39,707
it's a wonderful opportunity to create something positive

1268
00:54:39,787 --> 00:54:40,467
and life-changing.

1269
00:54:41,707 --> 00:54:45,169
In closing, NWC champion Thor Akerlund

1270
00:54:45,189 --> 00:54:46,449
said something to me that stuck with me.

1271
00:54:46,829 --> 00:54:48,410
He even said it in the Ecstasy of Order movie,

1272
00:54:48,430 --> 00:54:50,311
and I'd like to expand upon it a little here.

1273
00:54:50,951 --> 00:54:52,852
Of all games, Tetris is the most like life.

1274
00:54:53,492 --> 00:54:55,313
Death is imminent, life isn't fair,

1275
00:54:55,873 --> 00:54:57,073
but if you can deal with what they give you

1276
00:54:57,113 --> 00:54:59,074
and break through, that's what makes you a winner.

